It is often useful to check if a collection contain the same elements ignoring their position if the collection is supposed to represent a set of value.

However there is no easy way to do that even when using ES6 Set there is no easy way to compare two sets for elements equality as `new Set([1, 2, 3]) == new Set([1, 3, 2])` yields `false`.

Currently using lodash one can write things like `_.isEmpty(_.xor(array1, array2))` or `_.isEmpty(_.difference(array1, array2)) && _.isEmpty(_.difference(array2, array1))`.

However having a dedicated method would make code more readable and would reveal the intent better.

A simple implementation could be the following

``` javascript
function equalIgnoringIndex(collection1, collection2) {
  return _.every(collection1, function(element) { return _.includes(collection2, element) }) 
      && _.every(collection2, function(element) { return _.includes(collection1, element) });
}
```

this would be a lot like `_.get`, but if the object path returns `undefined` the `defaultValue` would be set on the object path and then returned. 

The code would look a lot like this

```
_.setDefault = function(object, path, toSet){
    return _.get(object, path, _.set(object, path, toSet));
};
```

this would be great for when you want to share references of objects or classes at a particular path but create new instances if it does not yet exist.

Usage 

``` Javascript
var SomeClass = FrameworkClass.extend(<someObject>);
var x = {}
_.setDefault(x, 'y.z', new SomeClass())
// → <newClass>
// x = { y: { z: <newClass>}}

var x = { y: { z: oldClass}}
_.setDefault(x, 'y.z', new SomeClass())
// → <oldClass>
//var x = { y: { z: <oldClass>}}
```

