I'm curious what lodash's documented behavior is when `_.get()` is given an ambiguous key on a potentially ambiguous object.

```
const obj1 = { a: { b: { c: 1 }, 'b.c': 2 }, 'a.b.c': 3 }
_.get(obj1, 'a.b.c') 
//=> 3
delete obj1['a.b.c']
obj1 
// => { a: { b: { c: 1 }, 'b.c': 2 } }
_.get(obj1, 'a.b.c') 
//=> 1
```

The behavior becomes most obvious when working with, say, Mongo statements.

```
const update = { $set: { 'profile.firstName': 'Bob' } };
_.get(update, '$set.profile.firstName')
//=> undefined
_.get(_.get(update, '$set'), 'profile.firstName');
//=> 'Bob'
```

Correct me if I'm wrong, but the behavior appears to be "if a root level key matches the query, return it. Otherwise, treat every period as a nested object and return the most deeply nested result of the query."

Would more consistent behavior be preferable? Like "always returns the least nested matching key"? Otherwise, would more complete documentation about this behavior be desirable?

Thanks!

